\begin_layout Section
Two-Level System in 1D EM field
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Setting: Spontaneous Emission
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's consider a two leve electronic system with energy 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{0}<\varepsilon_{1}$
\end_inset

 in diabatic basis: 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \left|0\right\rangle ,\left|1\right\rangle \right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The system Hamiltonian is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{H}_{s}=\varepsilon_{0}\left|0\right\rangle \left\langle 0\right|+\varepsilon_{1}\left|1\right\rangle \left\langle 1\right|,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and the electronic states are only coupled via the dipole–field interaction:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{V}=-\int dr^{3}\widehat{\vec{\mu}}\left(\vec{r}\right)\cdot\vec{E}\left(\vec{r},t\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the transition dipole moment opeator can be written as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{\vec{\mu}}\left(\vec{r}\right)=\vec{\mu}_{01}\left(\vec{r}\right)\left(\left|0\right\rangle \left\langle 1\right|+\left|1\right\rangle \left\langle 0\right|\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the transition dipole moment is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\mu}_{01}\left(\vec{r}\right)=\left\langle 0\right|q\widehat{r}\left|1\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 The electronic Hamiltonian then becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widehat{H}^{\mathrm{el}}=\widehat{H}_{s}+\widehat{V}=\varepsilon_{0}\left|0\right\rangle \left\langle 0\right|+\varepsilon_{1}\left|1\right\rangle \left\langle 1\right|-\int\mathrm{d}r^{n}\vec{\mu}_{01}\left(\vec{r}\right)\cdot\vec{E}\left(\vec{r},t\right)\left(\left|0\right\rangle \left\langle 1\right|+\left|1\right\rangle \left\langle 0\right|\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The initial environment does not have any electromagnetic field presented:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{E}\left(\vec{r},0\right)=\vec{B}\left(\vec{r},0\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
 For 1D case, we set the longitudinal direction of the EM field to be 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 direction and the transverse field on the 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

 plane.
 We consider the radiation field restricted in one longitudinal direction,
 say 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{z}$
\end_inset

, so that the transverse field is on the 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

 plane,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vec{E}\left(z\right)=E_{x}\left(z\right)\hat{x}+E_{y}\left(z\right)\hat{y},
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vec{B}\left(z\right)=B_{x}\left(z\right)\hat{x}+B_{y}\left(z\right)\hat{y},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{y}$
\end_inset

 are the unit vectors.
 Also, the dipole moment can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vec{\mu}_{12}\left(\vec{r}\right)=\mu_{01,x}\left(z\right)\hat{x}+\mu_{01,y}\left(z\right)\hat{y}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

By applying Fermi's Golden Rule (FGR), we can derive the decay rate in 1D
 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
k_{FGR}=\frac{\varepsilon_{1}-\varepsilon_{0}}{\hbar^{2}\epsilon_{0}c}\left|\vec{\mu}_{01}\left(0\right)\right|^{2}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Ehrenfest Dynamics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
electronic system
\end_layout

\end_inset

Ehrenfest dynamics treat the radiation field classically and the molecule
 by quantum mechanics.
 The molecular density operator is propagated by von Neumann equation of
 the density matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\rho}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}t}\widehat{\rho}=-\frac{i}{\hbar}\left[\widehat{H}^{\mathrm{el}},\widehat{\rho}\right]\label{eq:vonNeumann-Ehrenfest}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Since Ehrenfest dynamics does not include any dephasing or decoherence,
 we can express the density of state in terms of pure state wavefuction
 (if the initial state is pure state) 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\rho}=\left|\psi\right\rangle \left\langle \psi\right|$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi\right\rangle =c_{0}\left|0\right\rangle +c_{1}\left|1\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 We can then write an equivalent equation of motion for the electronic wavefunct
ion (Schrodinger equation): 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}t}\left|\psi\right\rangle =-\frac{i}{\hbar}\widehat{H}^{\mathrm{el}}\left|\psi\right\rangle \label{eq:Schrodinger-Ehrenfest}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
radiation field
\end_layout

\end_inset

The time evolution of the radiation field is governed by Maxwell's equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial\vec{B}}{\partial t}=-\vec{\nabla}\times\vec{E}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial\vec{E}}{\partial t}=c^{2}\vec{\nabla}\times\vec{B}-\frac{\vec{J}}{\epsilon_{0}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The current density observable in Ehrenfest dynamics is given by averaged
 over the current operator and obtain:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vec{J}\left(\vec{r}\right)=2\left(\varepsilon_{0}-\varepsilon_{1}\right)\mathrm{Im}\left[\rho_{01}\left(t\right)\right]\vec{\mu}_{01}\left(\vec{r}\right).\label{eq:J_12}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Ehrenfest dynamics take into account the effect of quantum electronic system
 toward classical radiation field in a mean–field approximation manner.
 Note that the averaged current density is proportional to the electronic
 coherence.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
problems
\end_layout

\end_inset

Due to the mean–field nature of Ehrenfest dynamics, the method has the following
 problem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If the electronic state is initially in an eigenstate of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{H}_{s}$
\end_inset

 (for example 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{0}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1}=1$
\end_inset

), the averaged current of the system is zero.
 For stimulated emssion case where 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{E}\left(z,0\right)=\vec{B}\left(z,0\right)\neq0$
\end_inset

, Ehrenfest dynamics may capture correct physics since the dipole-field
 interaction generate the elcetronic coherernce and leads to stimulated
 emission.
 However, for spontaneous emission where the radiation field is absent initallly
, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{E}\left(z,0\right)=\vec{B}\left(z,0\right)=0$
\end_inset

, the dipole-field interaction and the mean–field current density are both
 zero.
 Ehrenfest dynamics results in no decay in the system and no spontaneous
 emission observed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For a non-trivial superposition state initially (
\begin_inset Formula $c_{0},c_{1}\neq0$
\end_inset

), Ehrenfest dynamics can predict qualitatively a decay corresponding to
 spontaneous emission.
 Quantitatively, however, the decay rate predict by Ehrenfest dynamics is
 in general smaller than the Fermi's golden rule (FGR) rate and has a linear
 dependence on the inital state.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
not satisfy detail balance in finite temperature
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In fact, we can show that,
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
(see EhrenfestToFGR note)
\end_layout

\end_inset

 in the weak copling limit, Ehrenfest dynamics yields a decay rate that
 depends on the electronic state: the population 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{11}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 takes an exponential decay form
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho_{11}\left(t\right)=\rho_{11}\left(0\right)e^{-\kappa\left(t\right)t},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the decay rate is proportional to the ground state population instantaneou
sly
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\kappa\left(t\right)=k_{\mathrm{FGR}}\rho_{00}\left(t\right).\label{eq:instant_rate}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This finding gives us an idea of how we can modify Ehrenfest dynmics to
 recover Fermi's golden rule rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Recovery of Fermi's Golden Rule
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Known that the Ehrenfest rate is proportional to the ground state population
 on the fly, we consider part of the FGR decay rate is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

missed
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in Ehrenfest dynamics.
 To recover FGR, we put the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

missing
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 decay rate of Ehrenfest dynamics back in the algorithm by introducing an
 additional population relaxation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
How do we choose the additional rate?
\end_layout

\end_inset

Formally, we append an additional term with super-operator 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal L}_{r}$
\end_inset

 that is reponsible for the additional relaxation: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}t}\widehat{\rho}=-\frac{i}{\hbar}\left[\widehat{H}_{\mathrm{ele}},\widehat{\rho}\right]+{\cal \widehat{\widehat{L}}}_{r}\widehat{\rho}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Then we can write the EOM for the population 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{00}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{11}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\mathrm{d}\rho_{00}}{\mathrm{d}t}=-\frac{\mathrm{d}\rho_{11}}{\mathrm{d}t}=-\frac{i}{\hbar}H_{01}^{\mathrm{el}}\left(\rho_{10}-\rho_{01}\right)+\left[{\cal L}_{r}\widehat{\rho}\right]_{00}=-\frac{2}{\hbar}H_{01}^{\mathrm{el}}\mathrm{Im}\left[\rho_{01}\right]+\left[{\cal L}_{r}\widehat{\rho}\right]_{00}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and for the coherence 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{01}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\mathrm{d}\rho_{01}}{\mathrm{d}t}=-\frac{i}{\hbar}\left(E_{0}-E_{1}\right)\rho_{01}-\frac{i}{\hbar}H_{01}^{\mathrm{el}}\left(\rho_{11}-\rho_{00}\right)+\left[{\cal L}_{r}\widehat{\rho}\right]_{01}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Now we recast the super-operator term in terms of rate equation, so that
 EOM takes the form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\mathrm{d}\rho_{00}}{\mathrm{d}t}=-\frac{\mathrm{d}\rho_{11}}{\mathrm{d}t}=-\frac{2}{\hbar}H_{01}^{\mathrm{el}}\mathrm{Im}\left[\rho_{01}\right]+k_{0\leftarrow1}\rho_{11}-k_{1\leftarrow0}\rho_{00}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{0\leftarrow1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{1\leftarrow0}$
\end_inset

 are state-dependent rate that compensate Ehrenfest dynamics.
 At zero temperature, we set 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
k_{1\leftarrow0}=0.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

To sum up with Ehrenfest rate given by Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:instant_rate"

\end_inset

 and recover 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{\mathrm{FGR}}$
\end_inset

, the additional rate must be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
k_{0\leftarrow1}=k_{FGR}-\kappa\left(t\right)=k_{FGR}\left(1-\rho_{00}\right)=k_{FGR}\rho_{11}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Hence, the EOM becomes a non-linear ODE
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\mathrm{d}\rho_{00}}{\mathrm{d}t}=-\frac{\mathrm{d}\rho_{11}}{\mathrm{d}t}=-\frac{2}{\hbar}H_{01}^{\mathrm{el}}\mathrm{Im}\left[\rho_{01}\right]+k_{FGR}\rho_{11}^{2}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The non-linear EOM for population is simply Ehrenfest dynamics Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:vonNeumann-Ehrenfest"

\end_inset

 with an addiational population relaxation term determined by the FGR rate.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
What should we do about the coherence.
\end_layout

\end_inset

We don't know the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[{\cal L}_{r}\widehat{\rho}\right]_{01}$
\end_inset

 in the coherence EOM yet since there is no available information that can
 help us determine it.
 But we know that the coherence must be increased when 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{0}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1}=1$
\end_inset

, so that it can induce radiation emission.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Ehrefest+R method
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here we propose an Ehrenfest+R method.
 To implement the actual propagation of the electronic system by the non-linear
 EOM, we need to do a wave function propgation by Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Schrodinger-Ehrenfest"

\end_inset

 then perform the additional relaxation on top of it.
 Also, we need to maintain energy conservation by rescaling the radiation
 field with the energy change of the system
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
electronic system propagation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
How to propagate in pure state description?
\end_layout

\end_inset

For every time step 
\begin_inset Formula $dt$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
we first propagate the wave function by Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Schrodinger-Ehrenfest"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{0}\rightarrow c_{0}-\frac{i}{\hbar}\varepsilon_{0}c_{0}dt-\frac{i}{\hbar}H_{01}^{\mathrm{el}}c_{1}dt
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{1}\rightarrow c_{1}-\frac{i}{\hbar}\varepsilon_{1}c_{1}dt-\frac{i}{\hbar}H_{10}^{\mathrm{el}}c_{0}dt
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
we rescale the wave function by the population change 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d\rho_{00}=-d\rho_{11}=k_{FGR}\rho_{11}^{2}dt
\]

\end_inset

 and keep the phase of the wave vector by rescaling 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
c_{0}\rightarrow c_{0}^{\prime}=\frac{c_{0}}{\left|c_{0}\right|}\sqrt{\rho_{00}+k_{FGR}\rho_{11}^{2}dt},
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
c_{1}\rightarrow c_{1}^{\prime}=\frac{c_{1}}{\left|c_{1}\right|}\sqrt{\rho_{11}-k_{FGR}\rho_{11}^{2}dt}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
radiation field rescaling
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Rescale the EM field
\end_layout

\end_inset

To maintain energy convervation, we have to rescale the radition filed according
ly as we apply the additional population relaxation.
 Since the energy loss of the system by 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal L}_{r}$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
d\varepsilon=dt\left(\varepsilon_{1}-\varepsilon_{0}\right)k_{FGR}\rho_{11}^{2},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

we rescale the radition field by the same energy.
 For spontaneous emssion, there is no specific diection or functonal shape
 that an radiation should be emitted in the EM field.
 So we design the following three mechanisms:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Induce electric filed in the direction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{p}=\vec{\mu}_{01}$
\end_inset

: We rescale only the electric filed by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vec{E}\rightarrow\vec{E}^{\prime}=\vec{E}+\kappa_{E}\vec{p}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 To keep energy conservation, we have the relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\epsilon_{0}}{2}\int\left|\vec{E}^{\prime}\right|^{2}=\frac{\epsilon_{0}}{2}\int\left|\vec{E}\right|^{2}+d\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 and we choose the scale 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

 with minimal magnitude of 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\kappa_{E}\left(d\varepsilon\right)=\frac{-\int\vec{E}\cdot\vec{p}\pm\sqrt{\left|\int\vec{E}\cdot\vec{p}\right|^{2}+\frac{2}{\epsilon_{0}}d\varepsilon\int\left|\vec{p}\right|^{2}}}{\int\left|\vec{p}\right|^{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Induce magnetic filed in the direction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{m}\equiv\nabla\times\vec{\mu}_{01}$
\end_inset

 (divergence-free vector to keep 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\cdot\vec{B}=0$
\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vec{B}\rightarrow\vec{B}^{\prime}=\vec{B}+\kappa_{B}\vec{m}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

to keep energy conservation:
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2\mu_{0}}\int\left|\vec{B}^{\prime}\right|^{2}=\frac{1}{2\mu_{0}}\int\left|\vec{B}\right|^{2}+d\varepsilon$
\end_inset

.
 We choose the scale 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

 with minimal magnitude of 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\kappa_{B}\left(d\varepsilon\right)=\frac{-\int\vec{B}\cdot\vec{m}\pm\sqrt{\left|\int\vec{B}\cdot\vec{m}\right|^{2}+2\mu_{0}d\varepsilon\int\left|\vec{m}\right|^{2}}}{\int\left|\vec{m}\right|^{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Induce a mixed rescaling both 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 direction: we randomly partition the energy shift into 
\begin_inset Formula $d\varepsilon=d\varepsilon_{1}+d\varepsilon_{2}$
\end_inset

 simply by 
\begin_inset Formula $d\varepsilon_{1}=\text{RN}\times d\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d\varepsilon_{2}=\left(1-\text{RN}\right)\times d\varepsilon$
\end_inset

.
 Then we shift the field by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vec{E}\rightarrow\vec{E}^{\prime}=\vec{E}+\kappa_{E}\left(d\varepsilon_{1}\right)\vec{p}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vec{B}\rightarrow\vec{B}^{\prime}=\vec{B}+\kappa_{B}\left(d\varepsilon_{2}\right)\vec{m}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Actually, it will be more accurate to do:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\epsilon_{0}}{2}\int\left|\vec{E}^{\prime}\right|^{2}+\frac{1}{2\mu_{0}}\int\left|\vec{B}^{\prime}\right|^{2}=\frac{\epsilon_{0}}{2}\int\left|\vec{E}\right|^{2}+\frac{1}{2\mu_{0}}\int\left|\vec{B}\right|^{2}+d\varepsilon
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Coherence changes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the pure state descriotion, we can actually derive what is the 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal L}_{r}$
\end_inset

 in the coherence EOM.
 Since the density matrix keeps in pure state, the coherence is effectively
 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{01}=c_{0}c_{1}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 We approximate the coherernce after two steps as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\rho_{01}^{\prime}=c_{0}^{\prime}c_{1}^{\prime*} & = & \frac{\rho_{01}}{\left|c_{0}\right|\left|c_{1}\right|}\sqrt{\left(\rho_{00}+k_{FGR}\rho_{11}^{2}dt\right)\left(\rho_{11}-k_{FGR}\rho_{11}^{2}dt\right)}\\
 & \approx & \frac{\rho_{01}}{\sqrt{\rho_{00}\rho_{11}}}\sqrt{\rho_{00}\rho_{11}+k_{FGR}\rho_{11}^{3}dt-k_{FGR}\rho_{00}\rho_{11}^{2}dt}\\
 & = & \rho_{01}\sqrt{1+k_{FGR}\frac{\rho_{11}^{2}}{\rho_{00}}dt-k_{FGR}\rho_{11}dt}\\
 & = & \rho_{01}\sqrt{1+k_{FGR}\frac{\rho_{11}}{\rho_{00}}\left(\rho_{11}-\rho_{00}\right)dt}\\
 & = & e^{i\phi}\sqrt{\left|\rho_{01}\right|^{2}+\left|\rho_{01}\right|^{2}k_{FGR}\frac{\rho_{11}}{\rho_{00}}\left(\rho_{11}-\rho_{00}\right)dt}\\
 & = & e^{i\phi}\sqrt{\left|\rho_{01}\right|^{2}+k_{FGR}\rho_{11}^{2}\left(\rho_{11}-\rho_{00}\right)dt}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{00}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{11}=1$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho_{01}^{\prime}=\sqrt{k_{FGR}dt}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho_{01}^{\prime}-\rho_{01}=\sqrt{k_{FGR}dt}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\mathrm{d}\rho_{01}}{\mathrm{d}t}=-\frac{i}{\hbar}\left(E_{0}-E_{1}\right)\rho_{01}-\frac{i}{\hbar}H_{01}^{\mathrm{el}}\left(\rho_{11}-\rho_{00}\right)+\sqrt{k_{FGR}}
\]

\end_inset

If
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{00}\neq0$
\end_inset

: we can furthur approximate 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\rho_{01}^{\prime}=c_{0}^{\prime}c_{1}^{\prime*} & = & \rho_{01}\sqrt{1+k_{FGR}\frac{\rho_{11}^{2}}{\rho_{00}}dt-k_{FGR}\rho_{11}dt}\\
 & = & \rho_{01}\sqrt{1+k_{FGR}\frac{\rho_{11}}{\rho_{00}}\left(\rho_{11}-\rho_{00}\right)dt}\\
 & \approx & \rho_{01}+\rho_{01}\frac{k_{FGR}}{2}\frac{\rho_{11}}{\rho_{00}}\left(\rho_{11}-\rho_{00}\right)dt
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

coherence change rate is then obtained by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho_{01}^{\prime}-\rho_{01}=d\rho_{01}=\rho_{01}\frac{k_{FGR}}{2}\frac{\rho_{11}}{\rho_{00}}\left(\rho_{11}-\rho_{00}\right)dt=\Gamma_{r}\rho_{01}dt
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
