\begin_layout Standard
We now consider a three level electronic system with energy: 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{0}<\varepsilon_{1}<\varepsilon_{2}$
\end_inset

 in diabatic basis: 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \left|0\right\rangle ,\left|1\right\rangle ,\left|2\right\rangle \right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The electronic system Hamiltonian is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{H}_{s}=\varepsilon_{0}\left|0\right\rangle \left\langle 0\right|+\varepsilon_{1}\left|1\right\rangle \left\langle 1\right|+\varepsilon_{2}\left|2\right\rangle \left\langle 2\right|,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The electronic states are only coupled by the dipole–field interaction:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{V}=-\int dr^{3}\widehat{\vec{\mu}}\left(\vec{r}\right)\cdot\vec{E}\left(\vec{r},t\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the transition dipole operator can be written as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{\vec{\mu}}\left(\vec{r}\right)=\sum_{i<j}\vec{\mu}_{ij}\left(\vec{r}\right)\left(\left|i\right\rangle \left\langle j\right|+\left|j\right\rangle \left\langle i\right|\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\mu}_{01}=\vec{\mu}_{01}=0$
\end_inset

, so that the electronic system construct a 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

-shape transistion.
 The current density observable in Ehrenfest dynamics is given by averaged
 over the current operator:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vec{J}\left(\vec{r}\right)=2\left(\varepsilon_{0}-\varepsilon_{2}\right)\mathrm{Im}\left[\rho_{02}\left(t\right)\right]\vec{\mu}_{02}\left(\vec{r}\right)+2\left(\varepsilon_{1}-\varepsilon_{2}\right)\mathrm{Im}\left[\rho_{12}\left(t\right)\right]\vec{\mu}_{12}\left(\vec{r}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The electronic system interacts with the incident light.
 We assume the incident light is a continuous wave (CW) field whose longitudinal
 direction is on the 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 direction:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E_{I,x}\left(z\right)=\frac{U_{I}}{\sqrt{\epsilon_{0}}}\cos\left(k_{I}z-\omega_{I}t\right),\ E_{I,y}\left(z\right)=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
B_{I,x}\left(z\right)=0,\ B_{I,y}\left(z\right)=\sqrt{\mu_{0}}U_{I}\sin\left(k_{I}z-\omega_{I}t\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{I}=ck_{I}$
\end_inset

.
 The incident light interacting with the electronic system will emit the
 scattering light described as 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{E}_{S}\left(z\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{B}_{S}\left(z\right)$
\end_inset

 and the total field is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vec{E}_{tot}=\vec{E}_{I}+\vec{E}_{S},
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vec{B}_{tot}=\vec{B}_{I}+\vec{B}_{S}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We are interested in resonance Raman scattering, where the incident light
 is on resonance with a particular excited state, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar\omega_{I}=\varepsilon_{2}-\varepsilon_{0}$
\end_inset

.
